FBIS4-3887 "drchi080_f_94005" FBIS-CHI-94-080 Daily Report 25 Apr 1994 Near East & South Asia Press Release on Border Talks With India Press Release on Border Talks With India BK2504125294 Delhi ISI Diplomatic Information Service in English 1155 GMT 25 Apr 94 BK2504125294 Delhi ISI Diplomatic Information Service English BFN ["Press release" -- issuing agency, place, date not given] [Text] 1. The second meeting of the India-China expert group was held in Beijing on April 21-22, 1994. The Indian delegation, which was led by Shivshankar Menon, joint secretary (North East) in Ministry of External Affairs, included representatives from the Ministries of External Affairs, Defense and Home Affairs, the Army Headquarters and the Survey of India. The Chinese delegation, led by Mr. Fu Xuezhang, deputy director Asian Department, Ministry of Foreign Affairs, also comprised of experts from their concerned departments. 2. The expert group reviewed the progress made at its first meeting held in New Delhi in February 1994 and continued deliberations on the tasks assigned to it under the agreement on the maintenance of peace and tranquility along the Line of Actual Control [LAC] in the India-China border areas. The mandate of the expert group includes assisting the Joint Working Group in clarification of the Line of Actual Control between India and China, redeployment of military forces along the LAC, other confidence building measures and verification methods. 3. At the second meeting, the two sides reached agreement on the work regulations of the expert group. This document, which spells out the mandate, future tasks and modalities of the expert group, was signed by the leaders of the two delegations on April 22, 1994. 4. Both sides also noted with satisfaction that the situation along the India-China LAC was peaceful. They also expressed satisfaction at the confidence building measures already in place between them and exchanged views on further such measures as envisaged in the agreement establishing the expert group. They also had in-depth discussions on urgent questions relating to the maintenance of peace and tranquility in border areas. 5. Both sides adopted a constructive and forward-looking approach in these discussions which were held in a friendly atmosphere. 6. It was agreed that the next meeting of the India-China expert group will be held in New Delhi around end of 1994. This meeting will be preceded by the seventh meeting of the India-China Joint Working Group in Beijing around the middle of 1994.
